<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="lint-megalinter-polyglot">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdlc-ai</group>
    <domain>sdlc-ai</domain>
    <summary>Run MegaLinter in CI as the single polyglot quality umbrella for repos with 3+ languages; pick a flavor for lean images; never use it as a pre-commit hook.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>lint</tag>
      <tag>megalinter</tag>
      <tag>ci</tag>
      <tag>polyglot</tag>
      <tag>sarif</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>lint</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-30</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>MegaLinter as the Polyglot Quality Umbrella in CI</title>
    <summary>Polyglot repositories (three or more languages, e.g., Python + TypeScript + Terraform + Markdown) MUST run MegaLinter in CI as a single GitHub Action or GitLab job. MegaLinter auto-detects the languages present, dispatches 100+ underlying linters in parallel via Python multiprocessing, and emits a unified SARIF report so the agent and the security UI both consume one feed. Pick a flavor (security, python, javascript, terraform, dotnet, cupcake) to keep the runner image lean. MegaLinter MUST NOT run as a pre-commit hook — its image is too heavy for the local commit lifecycle; reserve it for CI and let per-language tools (ruff, biome) cover the local hook floor.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>MegaLinter (oxsecurity, fork of GitHub Super-Linter) is the only one-call surface that covers 69 languages, 23 formats and 21 tooling formats — ESLint, ruff, hadolint, terraform fmt, ansible-lint, yamllint, markdownlint, shellcheck, golangci-lint, rubocop, php-cs-fixer, sql-lint, dotenv-linter, and more in one shot. The parallel Python multiprocessing engine is meaningfully faster than Super-Linter's sequential bash and produces SARIF that drops directly into GitHub Code Scanning's UI. The "one umbrella in CI, one native tool per language at the hook" split prevents the well-known anti-pattern of running MegaLinter locally (multi-gigabyte Docker pull on every commit) while still giving the agent a unified CI feed to fix from.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Polyglot repositories with three or more languages or stack zones (Python + TS + Terraform + Markdown is the canonical example).</item>
        <item>Monorepos where each package may use different linters and a single CI job is simpler than per-language workflow shards.</item>
        <item>Repositories that need uniform SARIF output for GitHub Advanced Security or GitLab UltimateSecurity.</item>
        <item>Quarterly hygiene scans that want every linter in one report without per-tool maintenance.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-language repositories — ruff (Python), biome (JS/TS), or golangci-lint (Go) cover the same ground with sub-second startup; MegaLinter's image overhead dwarfs the value.</item>
        <item>Local pre-commit hooks — MegaLinter's image is multi-gigabyte and adds tens of seconds of pull/start time, breaking the sub-second hook contract.</item>
        <item>Throwaway prototype repos with one or two files of code — install ruff or biome and stop.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="ci-only-umbrella">
      <p>Each linter inside MegaLinter is the same binary you would run locally — there is no benefit to running MegaLinter at the hook because it adds container start-up time without changing the rules. The umbrella's value is the SARIF aggregation step, which only matters once code reaches CI.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Polyglot repositories MUST configure MegaLinter as a CI job (oxsecurity/megalinter@v8 or pinned SHA) that runs on pull_request and push and uploads SARIF via github/codeql-action/upload-sarif. The same repository MUST NOT register MegaLinter inside .pre-commit-config.yaml, lefthook.yml, or .husky/pre-commit; pre-commit hooks MUST stay on the per-language native binaries (ruff, biome, hadolint, terraform fmt) so the local commit completes in under one second.</statement>
        <rationale>MegaLinter ships as a multi-gigabyte container and takes tens of seconds to start; running it on every commit makes humans use --no-verify and trains agents to do the same. Native tools at the hook give the same coverage on the staged diff in milliseconds, while the CI MegaLinter run ratchets up the gate with rules that need cross-file context (markdownlint, link-check, vale, gitleaks history scan).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .github/workflows/megalinter.yml
name: MegaLinter
on:
  pull_request:
  push:
    branches: [main]
permissions:
  contents: read
  security-events: write
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with: { fetch-depth: 0 }
      - uses: oxsecurity/megalinter/flavors/cupcake@v8
        env:
          VALIDATE_ALL_CODEBASE: false
          SARIF_REPORTER: true
      - uses: github/codeql-action/upload-sarif@v3
        if: always()
        with: { sarif_file: megalinter-reports/megalinter-report.sarifv1.sarif }
        ]]></code>
        <note>One CI job, SARIF feed lands in Code Scanning, agent reads it through gh api.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .pre-commit-config.yaml — DO NOT do this
repos:
  - repo: https://github.com/oxsecurity/megalinter
    rev: v8.0.0
    hooks:
      - id: megalinter
        ]]></code>
        <note>Adds 30+ seconds to every commit; humans bypass with --no-verify and the local gate dies.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Running both MegaLinter and the underlying native tool (e.g., ruff) twice in the same CI workflow because "the agent fixes faster from the SARIF".</description>
        <reason>MegaLinter already runs ruff inside; the duplicate run wastes CI minutes and produces two reports the agent has to reconcile. Use the SARIF feed only.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="flavor-selection">
      <p>The default oxsecurity/megalinter image bundles every linter and is multi-gigabyte. Flavors (security, python, javascript, terraform, dotnet, cupcake, ci_light) ship only the relevant subset — cupcake is the right pick for the common JS+Py+Markdown+YAML mix.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Repositories MUST select a MegaLinter flavor that matches the languages actually present in git ls-files. The selection MUST follow: pure Python → python; pure JS/TS → javascript; IaC-heavy (Terraform, K8s, Dockerfile) → terraform; mixed JS+Py+docs → cupcake; security-only quarterly scan → security. Repositories MUST NOT use the unflavored default image unless three or more flavor families apply.</statement>
        <rationale>The flavor changes pull time from minutes to seconds and runtime memory from gigabytes to megabytes. CI quotas, especially on GitHub free runners and on Hetzner self-hosted runners, are dominated by image pull; the flavor is the single biggest knob for keeping MegaLinter sustainable as a default gate.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# repo with TS + Python + Markdown — pick `cupcake`
- uses: oxsecurity/megalinter/flavors/cupcake@v8
        ]]></code>
        <note>Cupcake covers JS/TS, Python, Markdown, YAML, JSON, Bash and Dockerfile — exact match for the canonical small polyglot.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# same repo, default image — pulls every linter on every CI run
- uses: oxsecurity/megalinter@v8
        ]]></code>
        <note>Pulls Java, .NET, PHP, Ruby, Swift, Rust, Go and Salesforce linters that this repo will never touch; CI bill triples.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Disabling individual linters inside the default image to "save time" instead of switching to a flavor.</description>
        <reason>Disabled linters still ship in the image; pull time is unchanged. Only a flavor changes the image.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/.mega-linter.yml" purpose="Repo-root MegaLinter config selecting a flavor and SARIF output."/>
      <template path="templates/megalinter-action.yml" purpose="GitHub Actions workflow snippet wiring MegaLinter into PR + push with SARIF upload."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://megalinter.io/">MegaLinter documentation.</link>
      <link href="https://github.com/oxsecurity/megalinter">MegaLinter repository.</link>
      <link href="https://megalinter.io/latest/flavors/">MegaLinter flavor matrix.</link>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
